Congratulations!

69
00:08:22,140 --> 00:08:24,180
At the beginning of this video,

70
00:08:24,180 --> 00:08:29,020
we said that there are three vowel diphthongs in American English.

71
00:08:29,180 --> 00:08:30,500
You may ask,

72
00:08:30,500 --> 00:08:34,120
what about the vowel sounds /eɪ/ and /oʊ/?

73
00:08:34,700 --> 00:08:36,020
Great question!

74
00:08:36,740 --> 00:08:38,659
There's a debate among linguists,

75
00:08:38,659 --> 00:08:43,839
about whether these sounds are "monophthongs" or "diphthongs."

76
00:08:44,020 --> 00:08:46,100
Here's what we think:

77
00:08:46,100 --> 00:08:51,320
The vowels in diphthongs are connected with a long, gliding movement.

78
00:08:51,680 --> 00:08:53,080
On the one hand,

79
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:58,320
the /eɪ/ and the /oʊ/ sounds are pronounced with similar gliding movements.

80
00:08:58,640 --> 00:08:59,500
So,

81
00:08:59,500 --> 00:09:01,740
they are kind of like diphthongs

82
00:09:01,740 --> 00:09:04,940
and we even represent them with two symbols each.

83
00:09:05,640 --> 00:09:07,260
On the other hand,

84
00:09:07,300 --> 00:09:10,440
this movement with the /eɪ/ and the /oʊ/

85
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:14,940
is not as noticeable as with the other diphthongs.

86
00:09:14,940 --> 00:09:17,420
So, they are somewhere in between.

87
00:09:17,720 --> 00:09:21,480
We admit, they can be diphthong-ish,

88
00:09:21,480 --> 00:09:25,480
but it'd be more logical to consider them as single vowels.

